inform our decision-making. And so by really equipping everybody with those three things,

00:13:20.039 --> 00:13:25.479
and we talk about that truly from day one onward through professional development and one-on-ones

00:13:25.479 --> 00:13:32.679
and everything at system, it allows for I think a high degree of ownership and autonomy and

00:13:32.679 --> 00:13:36.200
sort of distributed decision-making around the company. And that's something I learned

00:13:36.200 --> 00:13:43.000
applying now again at another startup, but from seeing that manifest at a several thousand person

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:49.479
technology company that really valued that kind of thing. Absolutely. That's great. I see there's

00:13:49.479 --> 00:13:53.719
quite a few questions starting to come in now. And Mike, I see you put one in the chat. Do you want

00:13:53.719 --> 00:13:59.719
to jump in and ask that? Sure. So I was just interested to know what kinds of tools are you

00:13:59.719 --> 00:14:08.039
using to build these systems models or estimate parameters and how do you evaluate the kind of

00:14:08.039 --> 00:14:12.679
combined models of all these different parts against the outcomes that you're interested in?

00:14:13.559 --> 00:14:19.320
Yeah. I'll give you the couple of minute answer and then all of our documentation,

00:14:19.320 --> 00:14:23.000
all of our technical documentation is up on our website and would encourage,

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:28.359
if you have interest to get more insight into the science and technology behind it,

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:32.919
please read that. And our data science team has done a great job to communicate that, I think.

00:14:34.599 --> 00:14:44.760
So system is a platform that starts from identifying sources of raw statistical evidence

00:14:44.760 --> 00:14:50.440
in the world. And that evidence today exists in a number of different places. For us,

00:14:50.440 --> 00:14:57.880
we've identified three in particular. Those are the corpus of scientific literature in the world.

00:14:57.880 --> 00:15:03.000
So papers that get published every day in every part of science through the great work of the

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:09.159
research community and funding agencies to advance scholarship. The second is the advancement of

00:15:09.239 --> 00:15:16.200
open data and real world evidence that sits in data warehouses and portals and so forth,

00:15:17.080 --> 00:15:23.960
measuring things like COVID vaccination rates and vaccine hesitancy rates and so on and so forth.

00:15:25.479 --> 00:15:34.359
And World Bank figures and IMF figures and so on. And then the third is a growing volume

00:15:34.359 --> 00:15:41.880
of machine learning models out in the world predicting a whole host of outcomes from housing

00:15:41.880 --> 00:15:51.239
prices to food security and so forth. And so we've built software to identify evidence of

00:15:51.239 --> 00:15:58.760
a statistical association in any of those raw materials or the potential to compute one.

00:15:59.640 --> 00:16:05.400
So from a scientific paper, it's a retrieval project. From a data set, it's a computation

00:16:05.400 --> 00:16:11.640
project. It's time series analysis. It's actually running correlation analyses on data. From machine

00:16:11.640 --> 00:16:17.559
learning models, we've built R and Python packages that allow our teams today, and we'll eventually

00:16:17.559 --> 00:16:30.359
open this up, to compute the importance of features in predicting an outcome in a test set.

00:16:30.359 --> 00:16:35.799
And then we'll look at that as well, that feature importance as yet another input into the full set

00:16:35.799 --> 00:16:41.080
of inflows coming into systems. So we've got all these inflows coming in. Then we have a huge job

00:16:41.080 --> 00:16:48.440
of normalization and entity resolution. So yes, we recognize dozens and dozens and dozens and

00:16:48.440 --> 00:16:56.440
dozens of types of statistical association from odds ratios to RCT experiments to SHAP values to

00:16:56.440 --> 00:17:01.960
so on and so forth to correlation coefficients and all these things and the metadata around them.

00:17:01.960 --> 00:17:08.199
So the strength of that relationship, the controls that were put on that experiment,

00:17:08.680 --> 00:17:14.280
the sign, the direction, all sorts of attributes of that relationship we retrieve.

00:17:15.079 --> 00:17:20.599
And we have to make sense of being able to relate one data point, one piece of

00:17:20.599 --> 00:17:24.920
evidence to another. So we do all that work. And then we have to resolve on the name level

00:17:25.959 --> 00:17:30.920
that obesity is an important topic that our users want to be able to search for and understand

00:17:30.920 --> 00:17:37.000
what's the relationship between obesity and diabetes. But because there's lots of different

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:43.880
ways, metrics, variables of measuring obesity, body mass index, body mass index over 30,

00:17:45.160 --> 00:17:50.040
patient has declared themselves self-identified as obese, so on and so forth. All of those then

00:17:50.040 --> 00:17:55.800
need to be grounded within what we call the topic of obesity. So then that's the next part

00:17:55.800 --> 00:18:03.160
of our platform. Then all of this gets organized in a large-scale graph database. And then the

00:18:03.160 --> 00:18:08.680
way we traverse that graph database when a user searches system is not based on language,

00:18:08.680 --> 00:18:14.760
as I was saying. So if the core architecture, if the core information architecture of search

00:18:14.760 --> 00:18:19.560
and discovery today is based on language, right? So you search Google for housing prices,

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:26.040
Google's knowledge graph will relate housing prices semantically to home prices and real

00:18:26.040 --> 00:18:30.439
estate prices, and then rank that and give you the New York Times article at the top.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:37.800
System is saying, cool, we need to get to housing prices, but then what we're really interested in

00:18:37.800 --> 00:18:44.199
is in all of the factors that system knows one degree, two degrees, and so forth away are being

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:50.920
impacting housing prices or are being affected by it. And then we assemble all of that, visualize

00:18:50.920 --> 00:18:55.880
that in a graph, and present all of the evidence alongside that for the user. So that's the core

00:18:55.880 --> 00:19:01.400
proposition. And then we're building applications on top of that. But that's what you can find today

00:19:01.400 --> 00:19:03.560
at a very high level kind of how things work.

00:19:06.920 --> 00:19:12.119
Thanks, Adam. I see there was an anonymous question that came in first, which was,

