and historically haven't been scrutinized the same way that defense companies or, you know,

00:20:41.959 --> 00:20:48.119
energy companies might have been scrutinized by the public. I'm really encouraged by, you know,

00:20:48.119 --> 00:20:55.719
the general direction of our field towards greater sense of accountability for the bias in our work

00:20:55.719 --> 00:21:00.920
for the impact of our work for the unintended consequences of our work. But I think this,

00:21:00.920 --> 00:21:06.520
you know, it starts with establishing that as a culture, it continues in actually making sure

00:21:06.520 --> 00:21:11.079
it's practiced. But then one of the things we're trying to do, and we were very open,

00:21:11.079 --> 00:21:17.880
we sort of published a blog post about this a couple months ago, is our VP of product and

00:21:17.880 --> 00:21:22.439
engineering and our VP of a team we call global issues, kind of working on systems application to

00:21:23.959 --> 00:21:27.319
world problems like global health, where we're doing work with the Gates Foundation,

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:33.880
published a blog post on something we're calling release risks. So tech companies are used to

00:21:33.880 --> 00:21:38.760
publishing release notes, alongside all their major releases. And, you know, so here's great

00:21:38.760 --> 00:21:45.560
features we've just released. And our idea was we wanted to publish alongside our first major

00:21:45.560 --> 00:21:51.800
release, which was a couple months ago, all the things we see that could be unintended consequences

